[1] Stripe rust, wheat - new strain suspected
Date: Fri 30 Apr 2010
Source: Southwest Farm Press, Texas Agricultural & Mechanical (A&M)
University report [edited]
<http://southwestfarmpress.com/grains/stripe-rust-wheat-texas-0430/>


Stripe rust in wheat across Texas could be a new race
-----------------------------------------------------
The results are not finalized, but Texas AgriLife [TAL] believe the
crop is being damaged this year [2010] by a new or different race of
stripe rust. Because winter and early spring were cooler and wetter
than normal, conditions were prime for stripe rust, said Ron French,
TAL. "We first saw it in the wheat nursery, then in north Texas on a
soft red winter wheat." He said samples have been sent to a wheat
genetics lab where it will be determined if it is a new race.

"Some of the wheat that we thought had good resistance is showing a
potential breakdown," said Rob Duncan, TAL. "This could well have
been accentuated by weather conditions that are favorable for both
the pathogen and disease development. We will have to wait until
harvest to determine the economic impact," he said. "We have a
diversity of varieties planted."

Fungal inoculum may have built up and may be present in higher
numbers in 2011. The possibility of a stripe rust epidemic was
apparent in north Texas by the 1st week of April [2010], with
widespread infection levels, Duncan said. As of late April, stripe
rust has been observed throughout Texas except for the Panhandle.

"Since there has been an apparent race change, resistance in
previously resistant varieties should not be taken for granted,"
French said. "There is no substitute for field scouting."

[Byline: Kay Ledbetter]

