[2] Downy mildew - sorghum and maize
Date: Mon 26 Apr 2010
Source: Victoria Advocate [edited]
<http://www.victoriaadvocate.com/news/2010/apr/26/fr_joe_janak_042810_93938/?viewpoints>


Sorghum downy mildew found in local corn field
----------------------------------------------
A plant disease, sorghum downy mildew, recently developed in a corn
field in Victoria County. This disease, caused by a fungus in the
soil, occurred in the same field when sorghum was grown on the site
in 2008.

Sorghum downy mildew was a serious disease in the Upper Coast
counties during the 1960s and early 1970s, but since then, its
incidence has diminished due to fungicide treated seed.
Unfortunately, the seed treatment used in the past is not used
anymore, so sorghum downy mildew disease may increase again.

In the affected corn field, the incidence of downy mildew is less
than 5 percent. Infected corn plants may or may not develop ears.
Infected sorghum plants do not develop seed. Current recommendations
are that if the disease is present in a field, to rotate out of
sorghum for at least 2 years and plant a resistant hybrid in the
future. Crops such as soybeans, cotton, and rice are not susceptible
and can be used in rotations.

[Byline: Joe Janak]

