[Stripe rust
-------------
Stripe rust (also called yellow rust) of cereals is caused by the
fungus _Puccinia striiformis_ var. _striiformis_. It causes yellow
leaf stripes and stunting of plants with yield losses of 40 to 100
percent. The disease affects wheat, some barley varieties, triticale,
and a number of wild grasses. Spores are wind dispersed in several
cycles during the cropping season, and the fungus survives on living
host plants generating a "green bridge" between seasons. Disease
management includes the use of resistant varieties, fungicide
applications, and control of volunteer crops.

New stripe rust strains with increased virulence have been reported
in recent years from Europe, North America, Australia, and India and
are also suspected to emerge in China. Monitoring programmes are
important to recognise these emerging new strains and it can be
expected that they will differ in national or regional significance,
depending on the susceptibility of preferred cereal varieties.

Sorghum downy mildew
---------------------
Sorghum downy mildew (_Peronosclerospora sorghi_; SDM) is a damaging
disease of sorghum and maize crops. The fungus affects _Sorghum_
species, maize, teosinte, millet, and _Panicum_ species. Many common
grasses can serve as pathogen reservoirs. Plants can be systemically
or locally infected.

Symptoms of systemic infection may include chlorosis, stunting, and
premature death of seedlings, striking leaf stripes followed by
necrosis and shredding of leaf blades on older plants, and
occasionally white downy growth on leaf undersides. Symptoms of local
infections are less dramatic and usually result in necrotic streaks
on leaf blades.

The fungus overwinters as oospores in the soil and plant debris and
can also survive in perennial grasses. Spores can be spread within a
crop by splashing rain, wind, or mechanical means. Mycelium can be
found in seed embryos, but looses its viability when seed moisture
drops below 20 percent. Disease management mostly relies on crop
rotation, removal of infected crop debris and other inoculum, and
fungicide seed and crop treatments.

In maize, around 10 different species of downy mildew fungi in the
genera _Peronosclerospora_, _Sclerospora_, and _Sclerophthora_ have
been reported. A number of these pathogens can occur together, but
different species may be common in different areas.

